-<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"6";}i:10;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1311";s:4:"name";s:4:"ADHD";s:4:"slug";s:4:"adhd";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1311";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3627:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">If paying attention or being constantly in a need to move is a state you are in, there is a chance you are affected by attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder (ADHD).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">ADHD makes it difficult for a person to concentrate and stay in control in terms of their behavior. He or she may also be restless and in a need to be constantly active.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Though the symptoms of ADHD begin in childhood, it is not just a childhood disorder. It can continue through adolescence and adulthood as well. It is a chronic disease and can last through years or in some cases, the lifetime.</span>

<b>A few symptoms of ADHD:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Fidgeting while seated</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Moving around where attention is required</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Restlessness/ Anxiety</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Talking nonstop</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Being in a hurry to answer and talk</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Feeling troubled while waiting for his or her turn</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Interrupting or intruding on another</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Treatment for ADHD: There are currently no cures available for ADHD but a few treatments help reduce the symptoms. These include:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Therapy</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Organized Tables &amp; Scheduling tools like study planners and notebooks</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Education &amp; Training under the guidance of family and Mental health Â professionals</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Stress management techniques</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â </span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">Support groups</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, a motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done path-breaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, ADHD is </span><b>Not trusting the flow and process of life. </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for healing ADHD is: </span><b>I love and approve of myself and I trust in the process of life. I am safe.</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Other alternative therapies that have also given good results for treating this disorder are Meditation, Hypnosis, Life Coaching, Rebirthing, Pranic Healing &amp; EFT - Emotional Freedom Technique,NLP- Neuro-Linguistic Programming</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"3";}i:11;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1312";s:4:"name";s:3:"AHD";s:4:"slug";s:3:"ahd";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1312";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:15;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1248";s:4:"name";s:9:"Allergies";s:4:"slug";s:9:"allergies";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1248";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:251:"<strong>Cause of Allergies :</strong> You are allergic to someone who or yourself denies your power
<strong>Affirmation:</strong>The world is safe and friendly. I am safe. I am at peace with life.

-<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"5";}i:16;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1313";s:4:"name";s:19:"Alzheimer's Disease";s:4:"slug";s:18:"alzheimers-disease";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1313";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4322:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Forgetfulness could well be a characteristic feature of old age. However, Alzheimerâ€™s disease is an ailment that ruptures the memory of the people. It is a neurodegenerative disease that causes brain cells to die. Initially it messes up with the chronology of events and gradually progresses to forgetfulness of basic habits like eating and pooping too. Alzheimerâ€™s disease is the most common form of dementia.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The progression of Alzheimerâ€™s could be categorized into 3 stages:</span>
<ol>
 	<li><b>Preclinical stage:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Here the symptoms donâ€™t occur visibly but the ailment has already started growing.</span></li>
 	<li><b>Mild- cognitive impairment:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> This is when the symptoms start showing, however this is rather mild.</span></li>
 	<li><b>Dementia: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">At this stage, the ailment has progressed beyond complete cure.</span></li>
</ol>
<b>Symptoms</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A set of symptoms could well prove to be an indicator of the ailment. A few of the symptoms include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Diminishing ability to grasp or adapt to new information. This could also involve forgetting new appointments, misplacing personal belongings and so on.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Impairment of complex thinking, reasoning and so on.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Inability to use/ recognize simple tools or even most familiar faces.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Changes in personality.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Anxiety and excessive stress.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Causes</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Nobody can, perhaps, ever point at one factor and believe it to be the sole cause of the disease. However, accidents or brain injuries could be an immediate reason. Other causes of Alzheimerâ€™s include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Nerve damage</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Brain injury</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Bad lifestyle</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Chronic diseases such as diabetes and fluctuating blood pressure.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Old-age</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Genetics</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Environmental factors</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Treatments</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A healthy lifestyle, balanced diet, routine exercises and mentally stimulating exercises could be extremely helpful. However, there is very little available cure for the ailment owing to its late onset. Moreover, medicines cannot reverse the cells that have died. Medications, however are available to slow down the progress of the disease.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the things you must understand is that those suffering from the ailment need utmost care and patience thus, they cannot be left unsupervised even for a minute second. Therefore, various Alzheimerâ€™s centres also have day care options that are supervised or run by experts.</span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done path breaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of Alzhiemerâ€™s disease is: </span><b>Refusal to deal with the world as it is. Hopelessness and helplessness. Anger.Â </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness.Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for treating Alzheimerâ€™s is</span><b>: There is always a new and better way for me to experience life. I forgive and release the past. I move into joy.</b>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:20;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1344";s:4:"name";s:16:"Anger Management";s:4:"slug";s:16:"anger-management";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1344";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3908:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">In Dr. Les Carter and Dr. Frank Minirthâ€™s book - â€˜The Anger Workbookâ€™ raises an interesting question - "Will my quality of life be greater if I choose to hold on to my anger rather than releasing it?"Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Anger is a natural, though sometimes uncalled for or irrational, emotion that everybody experiences from time to time. It is also a healthy emotion. But itâ€™s unhealthy when it flares up all the time and you cease to control yourself in it. Such explosive anger may cause serious problems towards your relationships, your health and your rational decision making.Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Anger Thrives on unfulfilled needs that arise out of excessive dependencies, feeling controlled, believing myths such as â€œletting go of my anger means I am conceding defeat,â€ and â€œself-inflicted anger;â€ How Other Emotions Create Anger - such as pride, fear, loneliness, and inferiority</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Adrenaline and Cortisol are the two hormones which our body releases whenever we are angry. These are the same hormones that are released when we encounter stress. Our bodies are not developed to combat these high levels of Adrenaline and Cortisol over long periods or on a very regular basis, which may result in a serious health concern.Â </span>

<b>Express Anger. Not Rage - The Importance of Expressing Anger</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">If one doesnâ€™t deal with his anger, it may lead to anxiety and depression. It can also raise your risk of illness. Several researches have shown that Long-term anger has been linked to health problems like:Â </span>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">High Blood Pressure</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Heart ProblemsÂ </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Headaches</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Skin Disorders</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Digestive Problems</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">It can also be a primary cause which is linked to crime, abuse, and other violent behavior. Expressing anger should be learnt. While there are numerous benefits in - Learning How to Manage Your Anger. Learning an effective way of communication to channel the anger to resolve your conflicts can benefit all aspects of your life.Â </span>

<b>Treatments</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Is there a cure for anger? Anger is not something you can get rid of. Your choice of anger management differs depending on the person and situation. One should try out various options available to them at their disposal - as what works for your friend, might not work for you. The essential things to continue your treatment whichever works for you in reducing your anger. Given below are a few of the proven treatments to tame your temper:Â </span>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cognitive behavioral therapy</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Improvements in communication skills</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Focus on problem-solving</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Avoidance of problematic situations</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Humor and self-deprecation</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">You canâ€™t completely eliminate angry feelings. But you can make changes to the way those events affect you, and the ways in which you respond. By making the effort to keep your anger in check, you and the people close to you will be happier in the long run.</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"5";}i:23;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1224";s:4:"name";s:10:"Anti-aging";s:4:"slug";s:10:"anti-aging";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1224";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:254:"<b>Cause of Anti-Aging</b>: Social beliefs. Old thinking. Fear of being oneâ€™s self.Â Rejection of the now.
<b>Affirmation</b>: I love and accept myself at every age. Each moment in life is perfect.

-<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"5";}i:24;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1330";s:4:"name";s:17:"Anxiety Disorders";s:4:"slug";s:17:"anxiety-disorders";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1330";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3680:"<strong>Anxiety Disorders</strong>

Experiencing occasional anxiety is normal, and just your bodies reaction to fear in regular life situations--like the first day at a new job of school. But when anxiety is persistent and comes up in daily life, seriously hampering day to day activities it is an Anxiety Disorder. As per WHO (World Health Organization) 1 in 13 people suffer from an anxiety disorder, making it one of the most common mental illnesses. Children and teenagers under 21 are often prone to anxiety. Only â…“ of the people that are suffering from this disease recieve treatment, although itâ€™s easily curable.

<strong>Anxiety can manifest in different forms that include:</strong>
<ul>
 	<li>General Anxiety</li>
 	<li>Social Anxiety</li>
 	<li>Panic Disorder</li>
 	<li>Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder</li>
 	<li>Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder</li>
 	<li>Separation Anxiety</li>
 	<li>Selective Mutism</li>
 	<li>Unexplained Fears & Phobias</li>
</ul>
<strong>Symptoms:</strong>

Some of the common symptoms of Anxiety Disorders (when all other factors have been taken into consideration) are:
<ul>
 	<li>Heart palpitations</li>
 	<li>Shortness of breath</li>
 	<li>Excessive sweating</li>
 	<li>Tremors or twitches</li>
 	<li>Headache</li>
 	<li>Unexplained Fatigue</li>
 	<li>Insomnia</li>
 	<li>Nausea or upset stomach</li>
 	<li>Frequent urination or diarrhea</li>
 	<li style="text-align: left;">Fear of losing control or â€œgoing crazyâ€</li>
</ul>
<strong>Overcoming Anxiety Disorders</strong>

Whenever you become anxious or stressed, you induce a flood of the stress hormone cortisol and its consistent presence could damage parts of the brain that process memory and executive functioning. Getting relief for anxiety disorders is then imperative.

One of the first measures in Anxiety management is Medication. Another important and much neglected therapy that can help is Talk therapy. Talking about oneâ€™s condition openly to a qualified therapist can help to find the right solutions. Lifestyle changes are known to help: getting enough sleep and exercise is seen to bring about beneficial effects. But one must keep away from alcohol, caffeine and other mood-altering substances as they are known to have a negative impact.

<strong>Food can be medicinal. Given below are some foods that can boost brain health and reduce anxiety:</strong>
<ul>
 	<li>chamomile</li>
 	<li>turmeric</li>
 	<li>dark chocolate</li>
 	<li>yogurt</li>
 	<li>green tea</li>
</ul>
<strong>Going beyond the holistic approach</strong>

Traditional western methods are widely used for treating Anxiety Disorders by way of curing the disease but not its roots. Louise Hay, motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€ According to her, the main cause of anxiety is: Not trusting the flow and the process of life. This lack of faith manifests in our bodies as anxiety. One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness.

Her affirmation for healing Anxiety Disorders is: <em><strong>I love and approve of myself and I trust in the process of life. I am safe.</strong></em>

Other alternative therapies that have also given good results for treating this disorder are:

