{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1170";s:4:"name";s:24:"Chronic Fatigue Syndrome";s:4:"slug";s:24:"chronic-fatigue-syndrome";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1170";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"3";}i:61;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1373";s:4:"name";s:17:"Chronic illnesses";s:4:"slug";s:17:"chronic-illnesses";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1373";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"5";}i:62;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1285";s:4:"name";s:32:"Chronic Neck &amp; Shoulder Pain";s:4:"slug";s:26:"chronic-neck-shoulder-pain";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1285";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:250:"<b>Cause of Chronic Neck &amp; Shoulder PainÂ </b>: Refusing to see another's side or position. Stubbornness. Who/what is being a pain in the neck?
<b>Affirmation</b>: It is inÂ flexibility i see

-<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"2";}i:65;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1334";s:4:"name";s:19:"Clinical Depression";s:4:"slug";s:19:"clinical-depression";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1334";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:6769:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Depression is a serious mental health condition and mood disorder that causes persistent feelings of sadness, loss, fear, and anger that disrupt daily life. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Clinical depression is an invisible invader of oneâ€™s self. </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">It is a serious mental illness and manifests as:</span>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"> feelings of utter sadness accompanied with bouts of sudden crying </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">hopelessness, </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">loss of interest, anger, guilt</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">frustration, </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">even irritability (especially in adolescents) </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Physical and mental fatigue</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">disruptions in the normal sleep patterns</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">feelings of anxiety</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">numbed feelings</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Loss of confidence &amp; self-esteem</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Changes in overall weight and in appetite</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lack of libido</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Unexplained aches and pains</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Impaired thinking and concentration powers</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Thinking of suicide</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Doing self-harm</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">These symptoms can last for weeks or months or years and interfere with daily life. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The symptoms are not visible and unless the sufferer voices their pain, their malaise could go unnoticed and untreated for a long time. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â </span><b>Causes of Depression</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Depression is a complicated illness and its causes are not completely understood. From the studied cases and diagnosed, some of the factors that could lead to depression are:</span>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Traumatic situations caused by a deep loss or intense stress. This also includes postnatal depression experienced by some women after the birth of their child.</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Illnesses such as bipolar disorder</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Genetics or psychological factors dating back to childhood</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Long standing and/or life-threatening illnesses </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Children can be affected due to the adverse conditions at home(parental disputes) or school (being bullied or peer pressure)</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Seasonal Affective Disorder (SAD) - caused by the low light in winter</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sometimes, there is no cause at all but the symptoms appear and create havoc</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Treating Depression</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Treating depression goes a long way in improving the quality of life. Depending on the severity of the depression, it can be treated through drugs and or through alternative therapies known as Talking Therapies.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Some self-care method of controlling the severity of depression include:</b><b>
</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Exercise: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Regular physical exercise releases endorphins, the feel-good hormones and this can improve the mood.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Diet: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">A healthy diet rich in vitamins and minerals can help. Avoid drinks, drugs and caffeine as they make the depression worse.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Building bonds:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Developing and strengthening relationships with family and friends help in keeping depression at bay.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Remaining stress-free:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Following a daily routine that promotes overall wellbeing and reduces stress is important in preventing and even managing depression.</span>

<b>Going beyond the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œ</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Illness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€ </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of </span><b>Depression </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">is: Anger you feel you do not have a right to have. Hopelessness. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for healing Depression is</span><b>: </b><b><i>Â </i></b><b><i>I now go beyond other peopleâ€™s fears and limitations. I create my own life. </i></b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Other alternative therapies that have also given good results for treating this disorder are: </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Past Life Regression, Spiritual Counseling, Life Coach, Meditation, Access Bar, Emotional Freedom Technique, Neuro-Linguistic Programming Therapy, Homeopathy, Rebirthing, Pranic Healing</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:2:"42";}i:67;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1261";s:4:"name";s:4:"Cold";s:4:"slug";s:4:"cold";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1261";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4689:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">The common cold is a viral infection of the throat and nose. Common colds are usually harmless and may not be severe.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Worldwide, children younger than 6 years have a higher risk of having common colds. Older adults can also experience two or three colds in a year. On an average, younger children develop up to 8 colds in a year with older adults only having up to 4 colds.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Most people affected by common cold recover within 3 days to a week. However, recovery might take longer in people who smoke. Most symptoms of common colds appear within 3 days of exposure to the virus.Â </span>

<b>Although the signs and symptoms vary from person to person, the general signs include:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cough</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sore throat</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Runny nose</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Congestion</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Frequent sneezing</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Â </span><b>Risk Factors For Common Cold</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The following factors can increase your risk of developing a cold:</span>

<b>Age: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Younger children of age six and below have a higher risk of cold.</span>

<b>Weak immune system: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">People with chronic illnesses or weak immune system have a higher risk of developing cold.</span>

<b>Season: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Both adults and children are likely to develop colds in falls and winters. Nevertheless, common cold can develop at any time.</span>

<b>Smoking: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Smoking can cause and in fact, lead to severe cases.</span>

<b>Causes Of Common Cold</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">While different types of viruses can cause a cold, rhinoviruses are the most common of them all.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">These viruses get into the body through the eyes, mouth or nose. They can also spread through air droplets of an infected person whenever they sneeze or cough.</span>

<b>Healthy ways to Prevent Common Cold</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">There's no special drug or vaccine to cure a cold, but implementing some lifestyle changes can reduce your risk of contacting cold virus:</span>

<b>Keep your hands clean: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Always wash your hands thoroughly with soap and water, and educate your children on the health importance of a clean hand.</span>

<b>Â </b>

<b>Disinfect your items: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Clean your bathroom and kitchen countertop using disinfectant-more importantly, if you have someone with a cold.</span>

<b>Tissues: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use tissues whenever you sneeze and cough. Throw away used tissues immediately after use, and wash your hands afterwards.</span>

<b>Drink more fluid: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Drinking plenty of fluids (especially water) is a very important step to take when you have a common cold. Because common cold leads to sweats and runny noses which increase the amount of water you lose, it's important to keep the body hydrated and replace the lost water by drinking more fluid.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Drink up to eight 250 mL cups daily. However, pregnant women should drink more.</span>

<b>Other fluid options for common cold include:</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ginger ale</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Herbal tea</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Honey and lemon tea</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ginger tea</span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, Motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of common cold is: </span><b>Too much going on at once. Mental confusion, disorder. Small hurts.</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the ways of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations.Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for healing common cold is: </span><b>I allow my mind to relax and be at peace. Clarity and harmony are within me and all around me</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.Â </span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"8";}i:68;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1193";s:4:"name";s:12:"Colon Cancer";s:4:"slug";s:12:"colon-cancer";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1193";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4437:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Colon cancer is cancer that grows in the large intestine. Most times, it starts as small, noncancerous cells which over time develop into colon cancer.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Globally, colon cancer is the third most-diagnosed cancer and the fourth cause of cancer death worldwide and may increase by up to 60% by 2030.</span>

<b>Symptoms Of Colon Cancer</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Most cases of colon cancer start with no symptoms in the early stage.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">However, general symptoms include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><b>A </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">change in bowel function.</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">This includes constipation and diarrhea - In fact, a rapid change (frequency) in the consistency of stool which usually lasts for up to a month.</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Blood In Stool</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Constant discomfort or pain in the abdominal regionÂ </span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Feeling like you still have some left</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fatigue</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Unplanned weight loss</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Causes Of Colon Cancer</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Doctors donâ€™t know the actual cause of colon cancer. However, available studies show that they can be caused by an abnormality in the DNA of the colon cells.</span>

<b>Risk Factors Of Colon Cancer</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Some factors can trigger the occurrence of this cancer are as given below:</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Most patients of colon cancer are adults above the age of 50. Although it can occur in younger people, prevalence is high among older adults.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Other risk factors include the personal history of the ailment, conditions of an inflamed intestine, family history of the disease, smoking, history of diabetes and/or obesity.</span>

<b>Preventing Colon Cancer</b>

<b>Earlier screening for colon cancer</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Older adults, since they have a higher risk of colon cancer should get screened earlier. People with conditions such as diabetes or family history should get screened earliest.</span>

<b>Eat fruits and vegetables: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fruits and vegetables contain minerals, vitamins and other nutrients which help prevent cancer.</span>

<b>Reduce alcohol intake: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Itâ€™s better to stop taking alcohol. Seek help if needed.</span>

<b>Quit smoking: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Seek help from an expert on how to quit smoking.</span>

<b><i>Other ways include exercising regularly and maintaining a healthy weight.</i></b>

<b>What To Avoid</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Several studies have revealed that a diet with excess red meat can trigger the risk of colon cancer.Â </span>

<b>What To Eat</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to recent research, diets high in fiber can increase the survival rate for stage 1 patients of colon cancer.</span>

<b>Eat whole grain</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Whole grains can improve the treatment outcome. Also, studies shows that eating up to 2 ounces of tree nuts such as walnuts and cashew can reduce the risk of colon cancer by half. Other ways include exercising regularly and maintaining a healthy weight.</span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, Motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of colon cancer is: </span><b>Secret grief or deep hurt. Long standing resentments.Â </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the ways of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations.Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for healing colon cancer is: </span><b>I lovingly forgive and release all of the past. I choose to fill my life with joy. I love and approve of myself</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"2";}i:71;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1140";s:4:"name";s:30:"Congestive Heart Failure (CHF)";s:4:"slug";s:28:"congestive-heart-failure-chf";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1140";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:73;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1074";s:4:"name";s:12:"Constipation";s:4:"slug";s:12:"constipation";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1074";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4735:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ğ’ĞµÑ–ng ÑĞ¾nstÑ–Ñ€Ğ°tĞµd mĞµĞ°ns ÑƒĞ¾ur bĞ¾wĞµl mĞ¾vĞµmĞµnts Ğ°rĞµ tĞ¾ugh Ğ¾r hĞ°Ñ€Ñ€Ğµn lĞµss Ğ¾ftĞµn thĞ°n nĞ¾rmĞ°l. ĞlmĞ¾st ĞµvĞµrÑƒĞ¾nĞµ gĞ¾Ğµs thrĞ¾ugh Ñ–t Ğ°t sĞ¾mĞµ Ñ€Ğ¾Ñ–nt. Constipation cannot be regarded as a disease but may be an impending sign of another medical problem. Constipation is common among all populations and ages in the world. 16 of out 100 adults experience constipation at a certain time in their life.</span>

