<b>Affirmation</b>: I love and approve of myself. I see myself and what I do with eyes of love. I am safe.

-<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"6";}i:131;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1322";s:4:"name";s:16:"Headache Tension";s:4:"slug";s:16:"headache-tension";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1322";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4007:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Tension Headache, also known as stress headache is expressed by medical professionals as a mild to moderate pain often described as a feeling of a tight band around the head. We have all heard about migraine which results in nausea, well this is just a notch down. It has been reported that every year more than 100 lakh cases are registered in India for tension headache. This is also the most common type of headache, and yet people have not seen a decline in the number of cases for the same.Â </span>

&nbsp;

<b>Causes</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">As the name suggests, tension headaches are primarily caused by excessive stress. But the actual cause of tension headaches is unknown. Experts came up with a theory which stated tension headaches are stemmed from muscle contractions in the face, neck, and scalp, perhaps as a result of heightened emotions, tension or stress.Â </span>

&nbsp;

<span style="font-weight: 400;">But several types of research since then, have suggested that muscle contractions cannot be assumed as the only cause. Increased muscle tenderness, a common symptom of tension headaches, may result from a sensitized pain system, which is also known to cause tension headaches. It is common for some people to develop tension headaches after staring at a computer screen for a long time, or long after driving for long hours.Â </span>

&nbsp;
<ol>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Fatigue</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Dry Eyes</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> A Cold or Flu</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Caffeine</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Poor Posture</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Eye Strain</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Smoking</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> AlcoholÂ </span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Dehydration</span></li>
</ol>
&nbsp;

<b>Symptoms</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The pain is usually mild, but as this is also a chronic disease it can be intense. This is a type of headache that causes throbbing pain on one or both sides of your head, unlike migraine. It also doesn't share the same symptoms as that of migraine such as nausea and vomiting. </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">

</span>
<ol>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Dull Headache</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Pressure around forehead</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Tenderness around the forehead and scalp</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Sensitivity to Light and Loud NoisesÂ </span></li>
</ol>
&nbsp;

<b>Foods to Eat</b>

&nbsp;
<ol>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Sweet Potatoes</span></li>
