 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cough</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sweating</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Headache</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fatigue</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nausea</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Vomiting</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Causes</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Malaria is caused by a parasitic bite. However, here are the different stages of the transmission cycle:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Uninfected mosquito: A mosquito becomes infected by feeding on an infected person.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Transmission: Now whoever this mosquito bites, will get infected with the parasite.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Liver: Once they enter you, they enter your liver and cause you an infection.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Bloodstream: After a period, these parasites leave your liver and enter into your bloodstream. This is when you see the symptoms.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Transmission: In this stage, if an uninfected mosquito bites you, it will get infected - thereby continuing with this cycle.</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Malaria can also be transmitted in these ways:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">from a mother to an unborn child</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">through infected needles </span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">through blood transfusion</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Shoo away that mosquito with these home remedies!</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Cinnamon</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Turmeric</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Orange juice</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Grapefruit</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fenugreek seeds</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Mustard oil</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Ginger</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Holy basil</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sweet lime juice</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Apple cider vinegar </span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Neem leaf tea</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">One must know that a balanced diet and physical exercise could be very helpful too.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Some preventive measures include keeping the environment clean and getting rid of clutter and stagnating water. It is important to use mosquito repellents over all exposed areas of the body when you are going to be in a woody (or garden) area. </span>

<b>Treatments</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Until now, there are no vaccines available for malaria. Typically, antimalarial medicine kills the parasite. For years, scientists and researchers have been trying their best to find a way to develop these drugs further, however, it hasnâ€™t been very successful.</span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done path breaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€ </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of malaria is: </span><b>Out of balance with nature and with life. </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for treating malaria is</span><b>: I am united and balanced with all of life. I am safe. Â </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Alternative therapies for treating malaria have been widespread and age old. There havenâ€™t been a lot of medical developments in terms of antimalarial treatments and thus, alternative medicines help us in a big way. Herbal treatments or antimalarial herbal medicines, yoga, meditation, naturopathy, reiki, body massages, homeopathy, Ayurveda and acupressure can help you in healing faster too.</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:180;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1276";s:4:"name";s:12:"Malnutrition";s:4:"slug";s:12:"malnutrition";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1276";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:6474:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">A lot of us cannot quite understand the meaning of malnutrition fully well. While it is true that poor nutrition or imbalance of nutrition causes malnutrition in our population, it is not fully correct to say that only low levels of nutrition can cause this condition; yes, excess of nutrition can also call for malnutrition. According to the World Health Organization (WHO), â€œMalnutrition refers to deficiencies, excesses or imbalances in a personâ€™s intake of energy and/or nutrients.â€</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Broadly speaking, there are two facets of malnutrition- Undernutrition and overweight. </span>

<b>Under nutrition</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">, as the name suggests, is a condition that could cause stunting (low height for that age), wasting (low weight for that age) or serious deficiencies. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Overweight, on the other hand, causes serious ailments like obesity and diet-related non-communicable diseases like diabetes, cancer.</span>

<b>Symptoms</b>

<b>The early signs of undernutrition include:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lack of interest in food/ loss of appetite</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fatigue</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Irritability</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Loss of fat, muscle mass and body tissue</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Depression</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lack of concentration</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Perpetually feeling cold</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Low sex drive/ problems of infertility</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Low immunity/ recurrent illnesses</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Breathlessness</span></li>
</ul>
<b>The indicators of overweight include:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Over-eating</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Inability to control urge</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sudden increase in weight</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Obesity</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Causes</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Malnutrition can be caused due to various medical as well as environmental factors:</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">1)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Low intake of foods</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">2)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Psychological problems (such as depression, schizophrenia, bulimia)</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">3)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Mobility problems</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">4)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Digestive disorder</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">5)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Stomach ailments</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">6)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Alcoholism</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">7)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Poor food intake during motherâ€™s pregnancy</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">8)</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Lack of breastfeeding during infancy.</span>

<b>What to eat?</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Malnutrition is very closely related to what and how much you consume. Diet plays the most important role in the treatment as well as curing of this ailment. Always opt for a balanced meal that has adequate amount of carbohydrates, proteins, vitamins, minerals and plenty of fluids. Make sure you consume sufficient amounts of clean drinking water throughout the day.</span>

<b>Treatment</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the most popular treatments for curing malnutrition is improvising your diet. Most physicians will direct you to a nutritionist, in order to treat your deficiencies. Consuming dietary supplements can come in handy.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Karshayahara yoga, feeding of ambrosial nectar, reiki, naturopathy, Ayurveda as well as Homeopathy could be quite helpful in treating malnutrition too.</span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Traditional western methods are widely used for treating breakup, Louise Hay, Motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€ </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fat or Weight issues is: </span><b>Oversensitivity. Often represents fear and shows a need for protection. Fear may be a cover for hidden anger and a resistance to forgive. Running away from feelings. Insecurity, self-rejection and seeking fulfillment. â€“ Arms: Anger at being denied love. â€“ Belly: Anger at being denied nourishment. â€“ Hips: Lumps of stubborn anger at the parents. â€“ Thighs: Packed childhood anger. Often rage at the father.</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the ways of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for weight problems is:</span><b> I love myself. I am enough.</b>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"6";}i:181;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1337";s:4:"name";s:34:"Manic Depressive Psychosis ( MDP )";s:4:"slug";s:30:"manic-depressive-psychosis-mdp";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1337";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"2";}i:183;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1192";s:4:"name";s:24:"Melanoma ( skin cancer )";s:4:"slug";s:20:"melanoma-skin-cancer";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1192";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"2";}i:184;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1350";s:4:"name";s:18:"Memory Improvement";s:4:"slug";s:18:"memory-improvement";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1350";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"3";}i:186;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1205";s:4:"name";s:28:"MENSTRUAL DISORDERS IN WOMEN";s:4:"slug";s:23:"menstrual-disorder-pain";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1205";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4195:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">For a lot of women, menstruation occurs with little or no problem. They may experience pain in the back and stomach - for a minimal period of time and then get on with their life. Their periods occur at a fixed time gap of say 22-28 days.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">But for other set of women, menstruation could be a real pain. Apart from emotional as well as physical symptoms, these women could experience uncontrollable mood swings, terrible back, stomach and abdominal pain.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A normal menstrual cycle is the one that occurs once in 28 days indicating various changes in different parts of your body like uterus, breasts, ovaries and vagina. A normal menstrual cycle runs for about 5-7 days. However, you must understand that a set of factors like heredity plays a key role in your menstruation. Here are 4 common abnormalities that are experienced by women:</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">1)</span> <b>Abnormal uterine bleeding</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: This includes one of the 3 conditions- Irregular periods (bleeding between periods), no bleeding (amenorrhea) or heavy bleeding.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Of the 3 conditions stated above, heavy bleeding is the most common one. It is believed that 1 in 5 women experience this. Bleeding is considered to be heavy when it interferes with your life in a way that you may have to take leave from work or school and so on. A normal menstrual bleeding is about 5 tablespoons a day. In case of heavy bleeding, you may have to change your pad or tampons every hour (rather than 4 pads a day).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">2)</span> <b>Amenorrhea</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is the condition where you do not experience any menstrual bleeding. This could be due to menopause, pregnancy, stress and hormonal imbalance.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">3)</span> <b>Dysmenorrhea (severe menstrual cramps)</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">: Most women will experience some sort of painful menstrual cramps as a part of monthly routine. However, if this is unbearable and interferes with your walking or sleeping cycles, you may have to immediately call for help.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">4)</span> <b>Pre-menstrual syndrome (PMS)</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is a set of emotional, psychological as well as physical symptoms that occur right before a period. These severely rupture your lifestyle. The symptoms include:</span>
<ol>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">a) Swollen, painful breasts</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">b) Bloating</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">c) Terrible mood swings</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">d) Irritability</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">e) Anxiety</span></li>
</ol>
<b>Treatment</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">While we know that these disorders are caused due to hormonal imbalances, stress and heredity, there is very little that we can do in terms of treatment. However, there are multiple over-the-counter drugs that may solve your woes and give relief from painful symptoms. In extreme cases, you may be advised to undergo a surgery.</span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done path breaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€ </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of menstrual problems/ amenorrhea is: </span><b>Not wanting to be a woman. Dislike of the self. Â </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for treating amenorrhea is</span><b>:Â I am balanced and peaceful in all changes of cycles and know that I am loved.</b>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"7";}i:187;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1361";s:4:"name";s:15:"Mid-life Crisis";s:4:"slug";s:15:"mid-life-crisis";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1361";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:188;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1329";s:4:"name";s:9:"Migraines";s:4:"slug";s:9:"migraines";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1329";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:6201:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">When we talk of migraine we think of a very very bad headache. Yes, it is a neurological disorder characterised by pain that is restricted to one side of the head, could be throbbing or pulsing, lasting for up to 4 hours or even days at a stretch, despite pain relief measures. </span>

<b>The headache can be often accompanied by:</b>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;"> nausea, </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">vomiting, </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">difficulty speaking, </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">numbness or tingling, </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">sensitivity to light and sound and </span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">worsened pain when you move, cough, or sneeze</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â It is also possible to have these symptoms without any headache. </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Based on symptoms and clinical history, migraines are categorised into those </span><b>with aura </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">(classic migraines) and those </span><b>without aura </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">(common migraines).</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In a study conducted in Eastern India, the results showed that </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">about 14.12% of the respondents had migraine. The maximum burden was among women aged between 30 and 34 years.</span>

<b>Causes of Migraine</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">No definite cause(s) have been identified for migraines but triggers are many. Changes in brain chemicals, e.g. decrease in the level of serotonin can activate a migraine. </span>

<b>Other triggers include:</b>

<b>Emotional factors: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Stress, anxiety, depression, trauma</span>

<b>Diet: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Tobacco,</span> <span style="font-weight: 400;">caffeine or caffeine withdrawal, skipped meals, alcohol, chocolate, aged cheeses, Monosodium glutamate (MSG), fermented or pickled goods, yeast, cured meats, some fruits and nuts, dehydration</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Sensory overload:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Strong smells, loud noises, bright or flashing lights, sudden changes in weather</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Physical conditions: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Â Medication overuse (taking medicine for migraines too often), too much or not enough sleep, hormonal changes in women, Overexertion (too much physical activity), </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">low blood sugar and jet lag.</span>

<b>Managing Migraines</b><b>
</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Migraine sufferers wish they could pop a pill and get immediate relief from the debilitation that a migraine can cause. But since that is not a thing, the next best course of action is prevention. The frequency of a migraine attack </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">can be controlled by adopting these measures in oneâ€™s lifestyle: </span>
<ul>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">getting enough sleep</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">reducing stress</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">drinking plenty of water</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">avoiding certain foods</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">regular physical exercise</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">keeping a migraine log to see what foods, medicines or activities trigger the migraine</span></li>
 	<li style="font-weight: 400;"><span style="font-weight: 400;">A gluten-free diet can be helpful</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">There is no cure for migraines but Â doing these things can help to alleviate the discomfort:</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">1) </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Resting with your eyes closed in a quiet, darkened room</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">2) Placing a cool cloth or ice pack on your forehead</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">3) Drinking fluids</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><b>Going beyond the holistic approach</b><b>
</b><b>
</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Traditional western methods are widely used for treating Migraines. Louise Hay, motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œ</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Illness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€ According to her, the main cause of </span><b>Migraine</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is</span><b>: Dislike of being driven. Resisting the flow of life. Sexual fears. Â Â </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">
</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for healing Migraine is</span><b>: </b><b>Â Â I relax into the flow of life and let life provide all that I need easily and comfortably. I love Life! </b><b><i>
</i></b><b><i>
</i></b><b>Other alternative therapies that have also given good results for treating this disorder are: </b><b>
</b>Tibetan Bowl, Reiki, Ana Pana Sati Mediation, Crystal Bowl,Acupressure,Bach Flower Remedies, Rebirthing , Braintap, Hypnotherapy, Homeopathy.";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:191;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1358";s:4:"name";s:12:"Money Issues";s:4:"slug";s:12:"money-issues";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1358";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"3";}i:196;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1150";s:4:"name";s:26:"Myocardial Infarction (MI)";s:4:"slug";s:24:"myocardial-infarction-mi";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1150";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:199;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1319";s:4:"name";s:28:"Nerve &amp; Muscle Disorders";s:4:"slug";s:22:"nerve-muscle-disorders";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1319";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:202;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1566";s:4:"name";s:44:"Nutrition â€“ Malnutrition, Poor weight gain";s:4:"slug";s:39:"nutrition-malnutrition-poor-weight-gain";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1566";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"5";}i:203;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1256";s:4:"name";s:7:"Obesity";s:4:"slug";s:7:"obesity";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1256";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3848:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Obesity is the mother of all diseases. Need we explain about how there has been a spike in cases of obesity among children and youth? All that junk foods we gobble down and the lack of exercise has caused more harm than anything else.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In 2017, the New England Journal of Medicine released a study focusing on how the world is becoming obese. The pan-global research analyzed nearly 68 million people through 1980 to 2015 and found that 12 per cent of adults and 5 per cent of children could be classified as â€˜obese.â€™ Thatâ€™s how severe the ailment is.</span>

<b>Causes</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> for obesity may seem rather obvious to us. Here are some of the many reasons leading to obesity:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Genetics</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Junk food</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Lack of physical exercise</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Chronic stress</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Certain medications like antidepressants, insulin etc.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Hormone imbalance</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Excessive sugar consumption</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Treatments</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">What one should clearly understand is that fixing the causes could be of great help. In the current scenario, childhood obesity is a major problem for us to deal with. Children should be tested and evaluated for genetic as well as hormonal imbalances. Once they are diagnosed positive to any of these, they can be well directed to medications.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Bariatric treatment, surgery or medications could be a good option. However, we suggest you opt for a healthy lifestyle to see if that helps:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Exercise regularly: Something as simple as walking, jogging or cycling could help in the long run.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Play outdoor games like badminton, cricket or football that can help in some family indulgence time also.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Avoid sugary foods.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Say no to junk foods. Junk is actually what the name suggests, junk. It needs to be controlled and if possible, eliminated from your regular diet completely.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Reduce stress.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done path breaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her,Â  obesity is caused due to: </span><b>An inherent fear, need for protection and running away from feelings, insecurity, seeking fulfilment, and self-rejection.</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One way of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations. Doing this regularly can help to reduce the debilitating effects of this illness.Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for treating obesity is: </span><b>I am at peace with my own feelings. I am safe where I am. I create my own security. I love and approve of myself</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Apart from medications, alternative therapies could be of great help too. Some of these are Nutritional therapy, herbal therapy, acupressure, acupuncture or hydrotherapy too.Â </span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:2:"56";}i:204;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1333";s:4:"name";s:35:"OBSESSIVE COMPULSIVE DISORDER (OCD)";s:4:"slug";s:33:"obsessive-compulsive-disorder-ocd";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1333";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:2445:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Washing hands constantly, checking if the same door is locked about 3 times or more or wanting things to be aligned all the time could well be an indicator of OCD, but let us not be fooled by considering these traits as symptoms.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">To explain what OCD is, letâ€™s take this example: We have a lock system in our cars that rings an alarm each time somebody breaks it open. Remember this lock system is your mind. Now imagine the lock system is spoilt and sets off alarms in a sporadic interval. Each time it rings, you may go and check it over and over again, eventually after a point you realize it is the spoilt lock system and you calm down. But for those people with OCD, they know the alarm is spoilt but still find the need to check the car over and over again because it causes immense anxiety.Â </span>

<b>These are some symptoms to watch out for:</b>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Repetitive obsessions and intrusive, fearful thoughts.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Recurrent, disturbing mental images.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Â  Compulsions like aligning things at home over and over again (to control the anxiety).</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Parents must be watchful if their children, especially between 7-12 years of age, exhibit such symptoms.</span>

<b>Causes</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The thing with a lot of psychiatric illness is that you cannot pinpoint one cause and say what has caused them. However, those with a family history of OCD could be more prone to it than others.</span>

<b>Foods to eat</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">It is believed that a lot of ailments could be cured by eating right. For those suffering from OCD, it is advised to have foods rich in Omega-3 fatty acids like chia seeds, walnuts and low-fat dairy products like low-fat milk etc.</span>

<b>Treatments</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">OCD doesnâ€™t have a definitive cure, however, it can be treated through medication and various therapies like family therapy, behavioural therapy and so on.Â </span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Alternative therapies that could help in curing OCD include Reiki, Dr. Bach flower remedies, Pranic healing, Acupressure, Energy healing.</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:207;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1305";s:4:"name";s:16:"Orgasm Disorders";s:4:"slug";s:16:"orgasm-disorders";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1305";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"4";}i:212;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1198";s:4:"name";s:17:"Pancreatic Cancer";s:4:"slug";s:17:"pancreatic-cancer";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1198";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"2";}i:213;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1331";s:4:"name";s:13:"Panic Attacks";s:4:"slug";s:13:"panic-attacks";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1331";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:4248:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">A panic attack is a sudden feeling of intense fear that results in serious physical reactions even without any reason or impending danger. A panic attack is a very frightening experience. Globally, its prevalence is estimated between 1â€“4% of the world population.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">It is common among people of the late 20â€“30 age bracket. A panic attack occurs in women twice more than in men. Even though they are not deadly, their occurrence can be frightening and significantly ruin your quality of life.</span>

<b>Symptoms Of A Panic Attack</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Typically, panic attacks strike suddenly. They can begin anytime and anywhere: at the store, when you're driving, during a business meeting, or even in the middle of a sound sleep. A panic attack can occur frequently or occasionally. They are often followed by fatigue after it subsides.Â  They generally include some of the following symptoms:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">The feeling of an unknown impending danger</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fear of death</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sweating</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Short breath or tightened throat</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Nausea</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Pain in the chest</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Headache</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sense of unreality</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Shaking</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Causes Of Panic Attack</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Doctors are out of the loop on what causes panic attacks, but the following factors play a major role:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Stress</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Genetics</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Temperaments that reacts to stress or negative emotions</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Certain alteration to some parts of the brain function</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Â </span><b>Risk Factors Of Panic Attack</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Factors that trigger the development of panic attacks include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">A family history of the event</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Shocking life events, such as serious illness or death of a loved one</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">A traumatic event like a ghastly motor accident</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Major life changes like divorce or giving birth</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Smoking</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Unforgettable childhood physical assault</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Prevention Of Panic Attack</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">There's no clear-cut way to prevent a panic attack. However, the following steps may help:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Get immediate medical attention to prevent its frequent/worse occurrence.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Always adhere to your treatment rules</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Physical exercises are also recommended as a protection against anxiety.</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, Motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of panic attack is: </span><b>Not trusting the flow and the process of life.</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the ways of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations.Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for healing panic attack is: </span><b>I love and approve of myself and I trust in the process of life. I am safe</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.Â </span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:215;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1203";s:4:"name";s:4:"PCOD";s:4:"slug";s:4:"pcod";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1203";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3316:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ğ Ğ¾lÑƒÑÑƒstÑ–Ñ Ğ¾vĞ°rÑƒ sÑƒndrĞ¾mĞµ (Ğ Ğ¡ĞĞ…) Ñ–s Ğ° ÑĞ¾ndÑ–tÑ–Ğ¾n thĞ°t Ğ°ffĞµÑts Ğ° wĞ¾mĞ°nâ€™s hĞ¾rmĞ¾nĞµ lĞµvĞµls. Women suffering from PCOS are known to have more male hormone than females, which affects ovulation. In fact, it can affect the womanâ€™s ability to give birth. Over 10% of women within the child-bearing age have PCOS.Â  It Ğ°lsĞ¾ ÑĞ°usĞµs hĞ°Ñ–r grĞ¾wth Ğ¾n thĞµ fĞ°ÑĞµ Ğ°nd bĞ¾dÑƒ, Ğ°nd bĞ°ldnĞµss. Ğnd, Ñ–t ÑĞ°n ÑĞ¾ntrÑ–butĞµ tĞ¾ lĞ¾ng-tĞµrm hĞµĞ°lth Ñ€rĞ¾blĞµms lÑ–kĞµ dÑ–Ğ°bĞµtĞµs Ğ°nd hĞµĞ°rt dÑ–sĞµĞ°sĞµ. Most women who have PCOS are unaware of it.</span>

