<b>Symptoms Of Sleep Apnea</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The most common signs and symptoms of sleep apnea include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Loud snoring</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Headache that occurs only in the morning</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Gasping for air during sleep</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Trouble with sleeping</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Irritability</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Â </b>

<b>Causes Of Sleep Apnea</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Medically, sleep apnea occurs when the muscles located at the end of the throat are relaxed.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">This relaxed muscle makes your airways narrower whenever you breathe in which reduces the amount of air flowing in. The brain detects your struggle with breathing and rouses you from sleep so the airways can be reopened. The awakening process is so brief that you may not remember it.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">In some other severe (and rare) form of Sleep Apnea, the brain refuses to send signals to the breathing muscles.</span>

<b>Who can be affected:</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The sleep disorder can affect anyone, not leaving out children. But a number of factors that trigger its occurrence include:</span>

<b>Obesity: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Excessive weight increases the risk of sleep apnea. Fats present in the upper airway can disrupt proper air flow.</span>

<b>Narrowed airway: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">People with narrow throat (which are often inherited) have a higher risk of sleep apnea.</span>

<b>Male: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">The possibility of males having sleep apnea is twice or thrice that of females. Also, women, after menopause have a higher risk.</span>

<b>Age: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sleep apnea is most common among older adults.</span>

<b>Family history: </b><span style="font-weight: 400;">Having a family history of sleep apnea might trigger the possibility of having one too.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Other factors include smoking, excessive alcohol intake, and heart disorder.</span>

<b>Lifestyle changes for the treatment Of Sleep Apnea</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">For mild cases of sleep apnea, a change in lifestyle is recommended. They include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Shed off some pounds</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Losing weight can open your throat and reduce sleep apnea.</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Stop smoking</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">Smoking increases inflammation in the throat. So it's advisable to stop smoking.</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Avoid using sleeping pills or taking alcohol before sleeping. It disrupts smooth breathing.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Maintain Regular Exercise: Regular exercise has a major influence on the quality of sleep. Yoga is also a good practice that will strengthen your airways.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Avoid caffeinated drinks and heavy meals at night.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Maintain a consistent sleep hour. It keeps you relaxed and you sleep better.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Bedtime steps to reducing sleep apnea</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Sleep on your side</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Don't sleep on your back. It makes it easier for your soft tissues and tongue to interfere with smooth breathing.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Move your head up</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Raise your bed's head by up to 6 inches. You can also use a cervical pillow for the elevation.</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Use a nasal dilator or nasal irrigation system to keep your nasal passage open at night.</span></li>
</ul>
<span style="font-weight: 400;">If these steps don't improve your symptoms or if you're suffering from a severe level of apnea, medical treatment might be recommended. There are certain devices that can aid free breathing during sleep. Other forms of treatment include surgery and therapy.</span>

<b>Going beyond in the holistic approach</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Louise Hay, Motivational leader and empowerment coach who has done pathbreaking work in supporting HIV/AIDS patients and their families, has said that, â€œIllness however mild or severe is an indicator of your emotional state, caused by your thoughts and focus.â€Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to her, the main cause of Sleep Apnea is: </span><b>Fear, anxiety, and feeling threatened.Â </b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">One of the ways of healing this is through saying or writing affirmations.Â </span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Her affirmation for healing Sleep Apnea is: </span><b>I lovingly protect myself with thought of joy and peace. The past is forgiven and forgotten. I am free in this moment</b><span style="font-weight: 400;">.</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:276;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1117";s:4:"name";s:26:"Solitary Nodule of Thyroid";s:4:"slug";s:26:"solitary-nodule-of-thyroid";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1117";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:285;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1389";s:4:"name";s:6:"Stress";s:4:"slug";s:6:"stress";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1389";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:3:"214";}i:287;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1339";s:4:"name";s:30:"Substance Abuse ( Addictions )";s:4:"slug";s:26:"substance-abuse-addictions";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1339";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"2";}i:288;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1349";s:4:"name";s:51:"Suicidal Tendencies / Behavior (Cognitive disorder)";s:4:"slug";s:47:"suicidal-tendencies-behavior-cognitive-disorder";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1349";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"3";}i:293;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1219";s:4:"name";s:25:"Thinning Hair / Hair Loss";s:4:"slug";s:23:"thinning-hair-hair-loss";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1219";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:294;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1199";s:4:"name";s:14:"Thyroid Cancer";s:4:"slug";s:14:"thyroid-cancer";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1199";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"3";}i:298;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1366";s:4:"name";s:22:"Toxic Work Environment";s:4:"slug";s:22:"toxic-work-environment";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1366";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:0:"";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"1";}i:300;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1279";s:4:"name";s:6:"Trauma";s:4:"slug";s:6:"trauma";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1279";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3310:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Trauma is a mental and emotional response of a person to an extremely negative incident. Although trauma is a normal response to horrible events, its after-effect can be so severe that they affect the victimâ€™s ability to live a normal life.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">According to NCIPC, globally, trauma is the number one cause of death among people from age 1â€“46.</span>

<b>Causes Of Trauma</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Trauma is usually caused by a serious negative event that results in a long-term impact on the metal and emotional stability of the victim. Even though most traumas are physically-induced, others are psychological. However, the common causes of trauma include:</span>
<ul>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Natural disaster</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Rape</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Death of a loved one</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;">Serious illness</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Being a prisoner of war</span></li>
 	<li><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Â  Sexual abuse as a child</span></li>
</ul>
<b>Symptoms Of Trauma</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Although the causes and symptoms of trauma vary, there are some general signs of trauma to check out.</span>

<b>Emotionally disorganized</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">People who just came out from traumatic events usually appear emotionally disorganized. They can be recognized by their shaken and disoriented attitude.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">They donâ€™t respond to conversations in a way that a normal person should. They often withdraw from the conversation.</span>

<b>Anxiety</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Another sign of a victim of a traumatic event is anxiety. Trauma-induced anxiety can be evident in situations such as nightmares, irritability, mood swings, edginess, and lack of concentration.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">People respond to trauma in various ways. In fact, relatives and friends may not virtually notice the symptoms in some victims.</span>

<b>Treatment Of Trauma</b>

<b>Trauma- Maintain a regular exercise</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">A regular 30 minutes exercise daily is good. Rhythmic exercises such as running, walking, basketball or even swimming engages your arms and leg</span>

<b>Add mindfulness components</b>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Rather than concentrating on the exercise or distracting yourself, concentrate on your body as you move.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Boxing, rock climbing, or martial arts are a good example of mindfulness exercise.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">There are several trauma management program options available to victims. Due to the unpredictably varying nature of the condition, there is no one-size-fits-all approach to treatment. Each patient has their own individual approach and treatments.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">The first approach is to aid the quick recovery of the physical effects of trauma. Burned skin, broken bones, and other organs that require a specific treatment will be treated before moving over to the psychological healing process.</span>";s:6:"parent";s:1:"0";s:5:"count";s:1:"2";}i:307;O:8:"stdClass":9:{s:7:"term_id";s:4:"1295";s:4:"name";s:7:"Typhoid";s:4:"slug";s:7:"typhoid";s:10:"term_group";s:1:"0";s:16:"term_taxonomy_id";s:4:"1295";s:8:"taxonomy";s:7:"ailment";s:11:"description";s:3485:"<span style="font-weight: 400;">Ğ¢ÑƒÑ€hĞ¾Ñ–d Ñ–s Ğ° life-threatening infection caused by a bacterium known as Salmonella Typhi. They are mostly spread through contaminated water and food. According to WHO, between 11-20 million people gets infected with TyphoidÂ  and over 128,000 people die from it annually. WĞ°shÑ–ng fruÑ–t Ğ°nd vĞµgĞµtĞ°blĞµs ÑĞ°n sÑ€rĞµĞ°d Ñ–t, Ñ–f ÑĞ¾ntĞ°mÑ–nĞ°tĞµd wĞ°tĞµr Ñ–s usĞµd.</span>

